Most people, in their daily lives, do not run too much risk of trading with=
 people subject to international sanctions. You probably aren=E2=80=99t buy=
ing your groceries from an Iranian front company. Meanwhile many=C2=A0busin=
esses, and in particular=C2=A0banks, do run this risk: If you are a big ban=
k, and someone comes to you to open an account, the odds that they are a fr=
ont for a sanctioned Iranian are not zero. And so banks have compliance dep=
artments that are intended to (1) detect sanctioned entities and avoid deal=
ing with them and (2) demonstrate to the authorities=C2=A0that they=E2=80=
=99re=C2=A0trying=C2=A0to do that, so that if any sanctioned entities slip =
through the cracks the reaction is =E2=80=9Coops, you missed one=E2=80=9D r=
ather than =E2=80=9Cyou are a criminal enterprise, here=E2=80=99s a huge fi=
ne.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0One thing about the broad and rapid sanctions imposed on =
Russian oligarchs in the last couple of weeks is that there will just need =
to be=C2=A0more=C2=A0of this. Banks have lots of experience with implementi=
ng sanctions, and other big international businesses in high-risk industrie=
s also have plenty of experience. But with all the new sanctions, more indu=
stries are higher-risk now than they were two weeks ago, and more businesse=
s will have to spend more time thinking about sanctions compliance.Also if =
you are planning to go to a soccer game you might want to  check in with yo=
ur lawyer first?The U.K. froze the assets of Chelsea Football Club owner Ro=
man Abramovich, as Boris Johnson=E2=80=99s government dramatically stepped =
up its sanctions against prominent Russians over the invasion of Ukraine.Ab=
ramovich and six others face a full asset freeze and travel ban, and are pr=
ohibited from transacting with U.K. citizens or businesses, the Foreign Off=
ice said in a statement Thursday. The move effectively derails Abramovich=
=E2=80=99s plan to sell Chelsea, which plays in England=E2=80=99s highest s=
occer league, and raises major questions about the future of the club.Chels=
ea won=E2=80=99t be able to sell new tickets for matches, including games i=
n the European Champions League, and the club=E2=80=99s merchandise stores =
will be closed. Player transfers are banned, as are new contracts.Here is t=
he general license from the U.K. Office of Financial Sanctions Implementati=
on that allows for a limited set of transactions with Chelsea; here is a su=
mmary. =E2=80=9CAs it is also prohibited to make funds or economic resource=
s available to any individual or entity subject to an asset freeze,=E2=80=
=9D you are not allowed to buy tickets. If you=E2=80=99ve already bought ti=
ckets, you are allowed to use them to go to a match. Once you=E2=80=99re th=
ere, you are allowed to buy refreshments, even though that involves giving =
money to a sanctioned entity, I suppose because it is cruel=C2=A0not to let=
 you buy a beer if you=E2=80=99re at the game anyway.=C2=A0You can=E2=80=99=
t buy merchandise from Chelsea, but you can=C2=A0resell it: =E2=80=9CThird =
parties who purchased or produced Club Merchandise prior to 10 March 2022 a=
re permitted to sell existing stocks of Club Merchandise, on the condition =
that no funds or other financial benefits are made available to the Club or=
 to=E2=80=9D Abramovich. There are other exceptions. If you=E2=80=99ve alre=
ady got a player transfer agreement or a broadcasting deal with Chelsea, yo=
u can make payments. Chelsea can keep paying staff and players. The team=C2=
=A0can spend money to travel to games,=C2=A0capped at=C2=A020,000 pounds pe=
r game.=C2=A0But, roughly speaking, no new deals.Sanctions are a bit of a s=
trange instrument. Chelsea Football Club is a corporate entity in the U.K. =
that is run by professional executives and employs lots of people, most of =
them in the U.K., most of them not Russians. It has its own bank accounts. =
The equity of Chelsea FC is owned by Roman Abramovich, =E2=80=9Ca prominent=
 Russian businessman and pro-Kremlin oligarch,=E2=80=9D according to the U.=
K. sanctioning notice,=C2=A0but Chelsea existed long before Abramovich; he =
acquired=C2=A0ownership=C2=A0in 2003. Chelsea is not exactly being sanction=
ed =E2=80=94=C2=A0Chelsea did nothing wrong =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=C2=A0Abramov=
ich is.If you wanted to get at Abramovich financially, one thing that you c=
ould imagine doing would be=C2=A0taking Chelsea away=C2=A0from him, for no =
compensation, and giving it to someone else. (Let the equity be owned by th=
e U.K. treasury, or by the Ukrainian treasury, or by the fans, etc.) Then C=
helsea could operate normally and Abramovich wouldn=E2=80=99t get any benef=
it from it. Alternatively you could just shut Chelsea down: dissolve the co=
rporate entity, fire everyone, kick it out of the Premier League, etc.This =
is not, however, generally allowed; governments cannot generally expropriat=
e property from people without some judicial showing that they came by the =
property illegally. Sanctions are not about=C2=A0taking stuff away=C2=A0fro=
m sanctioned individuals, but rather about freezing their stuff. You can=E2=
=80=99t send money to Abramovich, and he can=E2=80=99t spend the money he h=
as (in the U.K.), but they can=E2=80=99t take his money away from him exact=
ly. In theory this is temporary, and one day the war will end and he should=
 be able to get his stuff back.Another thing you could imagine would be=C2=
=A0not freezing Chelsea =E2=80=94=C2=A0letting it sell tickets and buy and =
sell players and generally conduct itself as a sensible soccer=C2=A0busines=
s under its professional management =E2=80=94=C2=A0but just preventing it f=
rom=C2=A0distributing money to Abramovich. The barrier would be between Che=
lsea and Abramovich, not between Chelsea and the outside world; Chelsea cou=
ld get and spend money but it couldn=E2=80=99t give the money to Abramovich=
.But sanctions mostly don=E2=80=99t work that way: =E2=80=9CAsset freeze re=
strictions also apply to any entities that are owned or controlled by Roman=
 Abramovich,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0says OFSI. Part of that is about ensuring compli=
ance: In general, if you let Abramovich-controlled businesses operate norma=
lly, they might try to operate in ways that benefit Abramovich (e.g. sendin=
g him money secretly to get around sanctions,=C2=A0spending money to buy st=
uff for him that he can=E2=80=99t buy because his money is frozen, etc.), b=
ecause after all he controls them. I suppose part of it is also about makin=
g sure that his position is really frozen: If Chelsea makes a lot of money =
in his absence and puts it in the bank, and then one day he gets unfrozen a=
nd collects the money, then in some sense the money was going to him all al=
ong. You don=E2=80=99t want him to=C2=A0accrue=C2=A0wealth, even inaccessib=
le wealth, while he=E2=80=99s sanctioned.And so you get this weird result w=
here Chelsea is allowed to operate, but=C2=A0badly; Abramovich is not allow=
ed to take money out of it, but you are also not allowed to put money into =
it (except for refreshments). It is hard to run a soccer club like this for=
 long. Presumably the expected result of a regime like this, most of the ti=
me, is that the frozen business withers and disappears; presumably with Che=
lsea the actual result will be that Abramovich negotiates a sale, the proce=
eds do not go to him, and the U.K. government grants a sanctions exemption =
to=C2=A0allow the sale. (A U.K.=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cofficial said the government =
=E2=80=98would consider an application for a licence=E2=80=99=C2=A0to sell =
the club but that Abramovich would not be allowed to benefit from the sale =
while he is under sanctions.=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0The sanctions cannot legally ta=
ke Chelsea away from Abramovich, but they can have the same practical effec=
t.
