      Nickel
   =20
 =20
We  talked on Tuesday=C2=A0about a hedging problem for nickel producers. If=
 you make nickel and the price of nickel goes up, you will make more money,=
 one day at a time, as you sell your now-more-valuable nickel. Meanwhile if=
 you have hedged your nickel production by selling nickel futures on a comm=
odities exchange, and the price of nickel goes up, you will get a margin ca=
ll from your broker demanding that you put up a lot more money=C2=A0right n=
ow. Your stock of nickel in the ground and in warehouses has become more va=
luable, but it is not easy to turn that all into ready money; your short po=
sition in nickel futures has moved against you, and that does=C2=A0require =
ready money. In the worst case, you run out of money and lose your business=
 even as it is becoming more valuable.There is a variation on this problem.=
 Commodities futures are standardized contracts for the future delivery of =
some commodity. The word =E2=80=9Ccommodity=E2=80=9D suggests that the comm=
odity itself is standardized, and that=C2=A0every instance of it =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0every bushel of wheat or barrel of oil or ton of nickel or pork belly=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0is the same. But of course this isn=E2=80=99t true.[1] The =
oil industry produces oil of different compositions and purity.=C2=A0 Typic=
ally for each commodity there will be one or two sorts of futures that are =
heavily traded and that people use as a benchmark, =E2=80=9Cthe=E2=80=9D pr=
ice of the commodity. And these futures will specify exactly what sort and =
grade of the commodity=C2=A0can be delivered where to satisfy the futures. =
London Metal Exchange=C2=A0nickel futures, for instance, are contracts for =
the delivery of Class 1 nickel, meaning nickel that is at least 99.8% pure;=
 the contract specifies what=C2=A0shapes and brands of 99.8% pure nickel ar=
e permitted. Lots of nickel, in the real world, meets that specification. L=
ots of nickel doesn=E2=80=99t.If you produce Class 1 nickel, and you are wo=
rried about price risk, you can=C2=A0hedge by selling futures. If you do th=
is, you will probably close out your hedge by (1) buying back the futures f=
or cash before they expire and (2) delivering nickel to some steelmaker or =
battery maker or other industrial user who is a customer of your regular bu=
siness. But you=C2=A0could,=C2=A0perhaps with a certain amount of shipping =
costs and administrative annoyance, instead=C2=A0deliver your nickel to  an=
 LME warehouse to physically settle=C2=A0the futures.=C2=A0If you produce=
=C2=A0other=C2=A0sorts of nickel, and you are worried about price risk, you=
 can also hedge by selling futures. The futures you can sell =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the liquid standardized ones with lots of buyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0are pret=
ty much LME futures on Class 1 nickel. That is not the kind of nickel you m=
ake, and you cannot deliver your nickel to satisfy the futures contract. Bu=
t it is still basically a good=C2=A0hedge. If demand for=C2=A0nickel goes u=
p, (1) the price of your nickel will go up and (2) the price of LME futures=
 will go up; if demand for=C2=A0nickel goes down, the prices of your nickel=
 and LME nickel will both go down. The futures are correlated enough with y=
our product that this is a sensible trade.On the other hand you have basis =
risk, the risk that the=C2=A0correlation will break down and LME nickel wil=
l be worth a lot more than your nickel. And you can=E2=80=99t arbitrage thi=
s away, because your nickel and LME nickel are not fungible.=C2=A0You=E2=80=
=99re short a lot of nickel futures, meaning essentially that you owe a lot=
 of nickel to the LME; meanwhile you own a lot of nickel, but it=E2=80=99s =
not the sort that you can deliver to the LME.=C2=A0Also if everyone on the =
LME=C2=A0knows=C2=A0that (1) you are a huge nickel producer, (2) you are sh=
ort a lot of nickel futures, and (3) you make the wrong kind of nickel, the=
n they can=C2=A0bet=C2=A0on the basis blowing out. If the price of LME nick=
el goes up high enough=C2=A0then you will get margin calls, you won=E2=80=
=99t be able to deliver nickel, you=E2=80=99ll have to buy back your LME co=
ntracts at a loss, the LME price will go up even more, and the people betti=
ng on this breaking down will make money.This may be part of what happened =
to nickel this week, as Chinese nickel tycoon Xiang Guangda and his Tsingsh=
an Holding Group Co.=C2=A0got short squeezed:The tycoon long believed that =
because he was the world=E2=80=99s biggest player and had ultra-low costs, =
he could wield unprecedented influence over the nickel market, people famil=
iar with the matter said. When prices rose above $20,000 he would consider =
shorting nickel, the people said, because his production costs in Indonesia=
 were as low as $10,000 a ton.=C2=A0Xiang was aware of flaws in his strateg=
y, people familiar with the matter said. Tsingshan=E2=80=99s nickel doesn=
=E2=80=99t match the grade used in settlement on the LME, so the contracts =
aren=E2=80=99t a perfect hedge. However, Xiang believed the risks to be man=
ageable, the people said, even as an unidentified nickel stockpiler control=
led at least half of the inventories on the exchange.=C2=A0And:A record-bre=
aking rally in nickel prices that led the London Metal Exchange to halt tra=
ding on Tuesday is putting increased pressure on the Chinese stainless stee=
l producer Tsingshan and its billionaire co-founder.Tsingshan, the world=E2=
=80=99s largest stainless steel producer, is rumoured to have built a big s=
hort position in nickel before a 250% rally in the price of the metal this =
week, which saw prices top $100,000 a tonne.That could put the company in a=
 difficult position, as it is not approved to deliver nickel metal into the=
 London Metal Exchange to close out its position. It also raises questions =
about the LME=E2=80=99s trading structure, especially as more nickel produc=
tion is geared towards use in electric vehicle batteries.=E2=80=9CIt can=E2=
=80=99t deliver against the LME because of the confines of the exchange str=
ucture which is not geared for the EV revolution,=E2=80=9D Caspar Rawles, h=
ead of data at Benchmark, said. =E2=80=9CTsingshan=E2=80=99s recent investm=
ents have been in battery nickel projects but the exchange is rigid in requ=
iring high purity Class 1 metal.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6The LME requires nickel =
that is 99.80% purity and in the form of cathodes, pellets, briquettes and =
rounds. Tsingshan=E2=80=99s nickel matte, however, has a 70% to 75% nickel =
purity.One simple form of this story is =E2=80=9Cthe price of nickel shot u=
p, and Tsingshan was long real-world nickel but short nickel futures, which=
 created a cash crunch that led to margin calls and the closing of the LME.=
=E2=80=9D Another simple form is =E2=80=9Cthe price of LME nickel shot up, =
and Tsingshan was short nickel futures and long non-deliverable nickel, so =
it lost a ton of money on the basis.=E2=80=9D[2] The first form suggests th=
at Tsingshan had a liquidity problem but not a fundamental economic problem=
: It was hedged but needed cash. The second form suggests that Tsingshan ha=
d an actual loss: Its hedge stopped working.[3]Anyway  the liquidity proble=
m is fixed-ish:The Chinese nickel company at the center of a historic short=
 squeeze has secured a package of loans from local and international banks =
to help it meet a wave of margin calls, according to people familiar with t=
he matter.Tsingshan Holding Group Co., which faces billions of dollars in p=
otential losses on short positions in nickel futures, won credit promises f=
rom banks including JPMorgan Chase & Co. and China Construction Bank Corp. =
in meetings that ran into the pre-dawn hours of Wednesday morning, the peop=
le said, asking not to be named since the matter is private. Some of the te=
rms, such as how much extra collateral Tsingshan needs to pledge, are still=
 under discussion, the people said. =E2=80=A6The bank loans are expected to=
 help Tsingshan address its immediate liquidity squeeze. With large nickel =
production facilities in Indonesia and China, coupled with surging prices a=
nd strong demand, the firm=E2=80=99s owner, Xiang Guangda, told bankers at =
the meetings that he=E2=80=99s confident his company can meet its obligatio=
ns, according to the people. He=E2=80=99s also reviewing his hedging strate=
gy and is considering exiting the bets against nickel, one of the people sa=
id.=C2=A0Yeah no when your hedges blow up, the exchange shuts down, and you=
 have to go to banks to beg for loans, you probably have to tell them that =
you are reviewing your hedging strategy. It has not quite worked, has it?Al=
so! On Tuesday=C2=A0I made a joke about melting down nickels (the coins, I =
mean) and like six people told me that it is=C2=A0illegal in the U.S. to me=
lt nickels. So don=E2=80=99t do that then. As I am constantly saying, nothi=
ng here is ever legal advice. Imagine melting down a nickel for $0.037 of m=
etals-arbitrage profit and then realizing (1) you have to pay for, like, a =
smelter or whatever and (2) you have to hire a criminal defense lawyer. Ima=
gine being prosecuted for it. The little blob of metal, Exhibit A for the p=
rosecution.
