      BlackRock
   =20
 =20
One rough model that you could have of BlackRock Inc. is that there=E2=80=
=99s a guy named Larry Fink and he directs how $9.5 trillion of money is in=
vested. The biggest shareholder of every public company is Larry Fink. =E2=
=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t like coal,=E2=80=9D  says Larry Fink one day, and coa=
l mines can=E2=80=99t get financed. =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t know Larry Fi=
nk had been made God,=E2=80=9D  says Sam Zell, but now you do.Another rough=
 model that you could have of BlackRock is that there is an enormous assort=
ment of people doing every sort of asset-management thing you could imagine=
, and they all technically work at BlackRock, but they work for different c=
lients with different mandates and sometimes they offset or contradict each=
 other. The BlackRock environmental, social and governance fund investor du=
mps coal stocks, but the BlackRock index-fund investor buys coal stocks. Mu=
ch of BlackRock=E2=80=99s money is in index funds, meaning that it just ref=
lects the market as a whole, but even outside of its indexing business Blac=
kRock is so big and so driven by client demands that it is=C2=A0a reflectio=
n of the whole=C2=A0market.There is some truth to both models, but the seco=
nd one seems both less popular and more true. Anyway here is Larry Fink, fr=
om January:In today=E2=80=99s globally interconnected world, a company must=
 create value for and be valued by its full range of stakeholders in order =
to deliver long-term value for its shareholders. It is through effective st=
akeholder capitalism that capital is efficiently allocated, companies achie=
ve durable profitability, and value is created and sustained over the long-=
term. Make no mistake, the fair pursuit of profit is still what animates ma=
rkets; and long-term profitability is the measure by which markets will ult=
imately determine your company=E2=80=99s success. =E2=80=A6It=E2=80=99s nev=
er been more essential for CEOs to have a consistent voice, a clear purpose=
, a coherent strategy, and a long-term view. Your company=E2=80=99s purpose=
 is its north star in this tumultuous environment. The stakeholders your co=
mpany relies upon to deliver profits for shareholders need to hear directly=
 from you =E2=80=93 to be engaged and inspired by you. They don=E2=80=99t w=
ant to hear us, as CEOs, opine on every issue of the day, but they do need =
to know where we stand on the societal issues intrinsic to our companies=E2=
=80=99 long-term success.Putting your company=E2=80=99s purpose at the foun=
dation of your relationships with your stakeholders is critical to long-ter=
m success. Employees need to understand and connect with your purpose; and =
when they do, they can be your staunchest advocates. Customers want to see =
and hear what you stand for as they increasingly look to do business with c=
ompanies that share their values. And shareholders need to understand the g=
uiding principle driving your vision and mission.And here is  Bloomberg New=
s yesterday:One hedge fund team at BlackRock Inc. saw Vladimir Putin=E2=80=
=99s invasion of Ukraine as a chance to buy more of the country=E2=80=99s s=
tocks. That decision has backfired.=C2=A0BlackRock=E2=80=99s Emerging Front=
iers Fund plunged over 10% in February, suffering the worst trading loss si=
nce it started more than a decade ago, according to people with knowledge o=
f the matter and an investor document seen by Bloomberg. The fund, which wa=
s managing $960 million at the end of January, is now down about 7% this ye=
ar, said the people, who asked not to be identified because the details are=
 private.Russia was one of the biggest long bets for the hedge fund at the =
start of February, with 9% of its gross assets invested in the country=E2=
=80=99s shares, after a research trip to the country in January, the docume=
nt shows. Sam Vecht, head of the team that manages the fund, told investors=
 he raised the bet further when the invasion began, one of the people said.=
=C2=A0Where does BlackRock stand on invasions, as a societal issue intrinsi=
c to its long-term success? Depends!=C2=A0
