      Deutsche Bank
   =20
 =20
One of the most mystifying concepts in finance is the cost of equity capita=
l for a big international bank. Basically a bank=E2=80=99s cost of capital =
is an amount of money that it does not make? =E2=80=9CWe need to make an an=
nual return on equity of 10%,=E2=80=9D banks are constantly saying while an=
nouncing that they don=E2=80=99t. The cost of, like, bread is the amount of=
 money that you need to pay to get bread. The cost of equity capital is not=
 like that. You have the equity capital, you really wish you could pay for =
it, you keep coming up short, and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s it? Every y=
ear you say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll get you next year=E2=80=9D? It is a stra=
nge state of affairs. Anyway:Deutsche Bank has promised investors it will e=
arn its cost of capital by 2025, something it has not done for over a decad=
e, as the bank announced new midterm targets on Thursday.Germany=E2=80=99s =
largest lender said ahead of its capital markets day that it aimed to lift =
its post-tax return on equity above 10 per cent over the coming three years=
. It is aiming to increase revenue by almost a fifth, to =E2=82=AC30bn, whi=
le further cutting its costs.The lender estimated its cost of capital at =
=E2=80=9Caround 10 per cent,=E2=80=9D according to a senior executive.=E2=
=80=9CThis is a super important milestone for us,=E2=80=9D the executive to=
ld the Financial Times. ...Since 2010, the bank generated accumulated net l=
osses of =E2=82=AC4bn and raised =E2=82=AC29.7bn in fresh equity, on averag=
e generating a return on equity of minus 0.24 per cent per year.In 2021, re=
turns stood at 3.8 per cent and analysts currently expect it to rise to 6.9=
 per cent by 2024.I suppose loosely speaking =E2=80=9Cour cost of equity ca=
pital is 10%=E2=80=9D means =E2=80=9Cif we don=E2=80=99t have a 10% return =
on equity our stock will go down,=E2=80=9D and that has generally happened =
to Deutsche Bank since 2009, but still it=E2=80=99s a strange sort of cost.
