om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Chelsea FC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most people, in their daily lives, do =
not run too much risk of trading with people subject to international sanct=
ions. You probably aren=E2=80=99t buying your groceries from an Iranian fro=
nt company. Meanwhile many=C2=A0<em>businesses</em>, and in particular=C2=
=A0<em>banks</em>, do run this risk: If you are a big bank, and someone com=
es to you to open an account, the odds that they are a front for a sanction=
ed Iranian are not zero. And so banks have compliance departments that are =
intended to (1) detect sanctioned entities and avoid dealing with them and =
(2) <em>demonstrate to the authorities=C2=A0</em>that they=E2=80=99re=C2=A0=
<em>trying=C2=A0</em>to do that, so that if any sanctioned entities slip th=
rough the cracks the reaction is =E2=80=9Coops, you missed one=E2=80=9D rat=
her than =E2=80=9Cyou are a criminal enterprise, here=E2=80=99s a huge fine=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing about the broad =
and rapid sanctions imposed on Russian oligarchs in the last couple of week=
s is that there will just need to be=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>of this. Banks=
 have lots of experience with implementing sanctions, and other big interna=
tional businesses in high-risk industries also have plenty of experience. B=
ut with all the new sanctions, more industries are higher-risk now than the=
y were two weeks ago, and more businesses will have to spend more time thin=
king about sanctions compliance.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also if yo=
u are planning to go to a soccer game you might want to <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTAvdS1rLWZyZWV6ZXMtcm9tYW4tYWJy=
YW1vdmljaC1zLWFzc2V0cy1pbi1mcmVzaC1ydXNzaWEtc2FuY3Rpb25zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMTA=
yMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV=
90ZXJtPTIyMDMxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4=
188491e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> check in with your lawyer first</a>?</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.K. froze the assets of Chelsea Football Club =
owner Roman Abramovich, as Boris Johnson=E2=80=99s government dramatically =
stepped up its sanctions against prominent Russians over the invasion of Uk=
raine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Abramovich and six others face a ful=
l asset freeze and travel ban, and are prohibited from transacting with U.K=
. citizens or businesses, the Foreign Office said in a statement Thursday. =
The move effectively derails Abramovich=E2=80=99s plan to sell Chelsea, whi=
ch plays in England=E2=80=99s highest soccer league, and raises major quest=
ions about the future of the club.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chelsea =
won=E2=80=99t be able to sell new tickets for matches, including games in t=
he European Champions League, and the club=E2=80=99s merchandise stores wil=
l be closed. Player transfers are banned, as are new contracts.</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMucHVibGlzaGl=
uZy5zZXJ2aWNlLmdvdi51ay9nb3Zlcm5tZW50L3VwbG9hZHMvc3lzdGVtL3VwbG9hZHMvYXR0YW=
NobWVudF9kYXRhL2ZpbGUvMTA1OTkyOS8xMDAzMjAyMl9PRlNJX0dlbmVyYWxfTGljZW5jZV9Gb=
290YmFsbF9NYXRjaGVzXy5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbaaab0d5" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">gener=
al license</a> from the U.K. Office of Financial Sanctions Implementation t=
hat allows for a limited set of transactions with Chelsea; here is <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6L=
y9hc3NldHMucHVibGlzaGluZy5zZXJ2aWNlLmdvdi51ay9nb3Zlcm5tZW50L3VwbG9hZHMvc3lz=
dGVtL3VwbG9hZHMvYXR0YWNobWVudF9kYXRhL2ZpbGUvMTA1OTkyOS8xMDAzMjAyMl9PRlNJX0d=
lbmVyYWxfTGljZW5jZV9Gb290YmFsbF9NYXRjaGVzXy5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCb=
aaab0d5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">a summary</a>. =E2=80=9CAs it is also prohibited to make f=
unds or economic resources available to any individual or entity subject to=
 an asset freeze,=E2=80=9D you are not allowed to buy tickets. If you=E2=80=
=99ve already bought tickets, you are allowed to use them to go to a match.=
 Once you=E2=80=99re there, you are allowed to buy refreshments, even thoug=
h that involves giving money to a sanctioned entity, I suppose because it i=
s cruel=C2=A0<em>not </em>to let you buy a beer if you=E2=80=99re at the ga=
me anyway.=C2=A0You can=E2=80=99t buy merchandise from Chelsea, but you can=
=C2=A0<em>resell </em>it: =E2=80=9CThird parties who purchased or produced =
Club Merchandise prior to 10 March 2022 are permitted to sell existing stoc=
ks of Club Merchandise, on the condition that no funds or other financial b=
enefits are made available to the Club or to=E2=80=9D Abramovich. There are=
 other exceptions. If you=E2=80=99ve already got a player transfer agreemen=
t or a broadcasting deal with Chelsea, you can make payments. Chelsea can k=
eep paying staff and players. The team=C2=A0can spend money to travel to ga=
mes,=C2=A0capped at=C2=A020,000 pounds per game.=C2=A0But, roughly speaking=
, no new deals.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sanctions are a bit of a st=
range instrument. Chelsea Football Club is a corporate entity in the U.K. t=
hat is run by professional executives and employs lots of people, most of t=
hem in the U.K., most of them not Russians. It has its own bank accounts. T=
he equity of Chelsea FC is owned by Roman Abramovich, =E2=80=9Ca prominent =
Russian businessman and pro-Kremlin oligarch,=E2=80=9D according to the U.K=
. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/=
aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMucHVibGlzaGluZy5zZXJ2aWNlLmdvdi51ay9nb3Zlcm5tZW50L3VwbG9=
hZHMvc3lzdGVtL3VwbG9hZHMvYXR0YWNobWVudF9kYXRhL2ZpbGUvMTA1OTkyNy9SdXNzaWEucG=
Rm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa14cc076" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">sanctioning notice</a>,=C2=A0=
but Chelsea existed long before Abramovich; he acquired<em>=C2=A0</em>owner=
ship=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481=
.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQ2hlbHNlYV9GLkMuI1RoZV9BYnJ=
hbW92aWNoX2VyYQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbb386d82" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">in 2003</a>. Che=
lsea is not exactly being sanctioned =E2=80=94=C2=A0Chelsea did nothing wro=
ng =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=C2=A0Abramovich is.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
f you wanted to get at Abramovich financially, one thing that you could ima=
gine doing would be=C2=A0<em>taking Chelsea away=C2=A0from him</em>, for no=
 compensation, and giving it to someone else. (Let the equity be owned by t=
he U.K. treasury, or by the Ukrainian treasury, or by the fans, etc.) Then =
Chelsea could operate normally and Abramovich wouldn=E2=80=99t get any bene=
fit from it. Alternatively you could just shut Chelsea down: dissolve the c=
orporate entity, fire everyone, kick it out of the Premier League, etc.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not, however, generally <em>allowed</e=
m>; governments cannot generally expropriate property from people without s=
ome judicial showing that they came by the property illegally. Sanctions ar=
e not about=C2=A0<em>taking stuff away=C2=A0</em>from sanctioned individual=
s, but rather about <em>freezing</em> their stuff. You can=E2=80=99t send m=
oney to Abramovich, and he can=E2=80=99t spend the money he has (in the U.K=
.), but they can=E2=80=99t take his money away from him exactly. In theory =
this is temporary, and one day the war will end and he should be able to ge=
t his stuff back.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another thing you could i=
magine would be=C2=A0<em>not freezing Chelsea</em> =E2=80=94=C2=A0letting i=
t sell tickets and buy and sell players and generally conduct itself as a s=
ensible soccer=C2=A0business under its professional management =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but just preventing it from=C2=A0<em>distributing money to Abramovich</e=
m>. The barrier would be between Chelsea and Abramovich, not between Chelse=
a and the outside world; Chelsea could get and spend money but it couldn=E2=
=80=99t give the money to Abramovich.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But s=
anctions mostly don=E2=80=99t work that way: =E2=80=9CAsset freeze restrict=
ions also apply to any entities that are owned or controlled by Roman Abram=
ovich,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly9vZnNpLmJsb2cuZ292LnVrLzIwMjIvMDMvMTAvY2hlbHNl=
YS1mb290YmFsbC1jbHViLXdoYXQteW91LW5lZWQtdG8ta25vdy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB6130023a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">says OFSI</a>. Part of that is about <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVy=
LmNvbS9kc3F1YXJlZGRpZ2VzdC9zdGF0dXMvMTUwMTg1Nzg2NjQxMTY1MTA3NA/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBf2eba5c7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">ensuring compliance</a>: In general, if you =
let Abramovich-controlled businesses operate normally, they might try to op=
erate in ways that benefit Abramovich (e.g. sending him money secretly to g=
et around sanctions,=C2=A0spending money to buy stuff for him that he can=
=E2=80=99t buy because his money is frozen, etc.), because after all he con=
trols them. I suppose part of it is also about making sure that his positio=
n is really frozen: If Chelsea makes a lot of money in his absence and puts=
 it in the bank, and then one day he gets unfrozen and collects the money, =
then in some sense the money was going to him all along. You don=E2=80=99t =
want him to=C2=A0<em>accrue=C2=A0</em>wealth, even inaccessible wealth, whi=
le he=E2=80=99s sanctioned.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so you get =
this weird result where Chelsea is allowed to operate, but=C2=A0<em>badly</=
em>; Abramovich is not allowed to take money out of it, but you are also no=
t allowed to put money into it (except for refreshments). It is hard to run=
 a soccer club like this for long. Presumably the expected result of a regi=
me like this, most of the time, is that the frozen business withers and dis=
appears; presumably with Chelsea <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWZlY3Rvci5jb20vY2hlbHNlYS1iZWxv=
bmdzLXRvLXRoZS11LWstbm93Lw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe7bee27f" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the a=
ctual result will be</a> that Abramovich negotiates a sale, the proceeds do=
 not go to him, and the U.K. government grants a sanctions exemption to=C2=
=A0allow the sale. (A U.K.=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cofficial said the government =E2=
=80=98would consider an application for a licence=E2=80=99=C2=A0to sell the=
 club but that Abramovich <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMGU5YmE1MDMtMzg=
xNS00NjQzLWI2NzItOGM5NTgxMDlhM2Rl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB28c4fc7f" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">would not be allowed to benefit</a> from the sale while he is under sanct=
ions.=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0The sanctions cannot legally take Chelsea away from Ab=
ramovich, but they can have the same practical effect.</p><table class=3D"l=
iveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=
