5px;">Nickel</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDgvbmlja2VsLWlzLWNhbmNlbGVkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAz=
MTAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDMxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBbe9a86fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> talked on Tuesday</a>=C2=A0about a hedging problem for=
 nickel producers. If you make nickel and the price of nickel goes up, you =
will make more money, one day at a time, as you sell your now-more-valuable=
 nickel. Meanwhile if you have hedged your nickel production by selling nic=
kel futures on a commodities exchange, and the price of nickel goes up, you=
 will get a margin call from your broker demanding that you put up a lot mo=
re money=C2=A0<em>right now</em>. Your stock of nickel in the ground and in=
 warehouses has become more valuable, but it is not easy to turn that all i=
nto ready money; your short position in nickel futures has moved against yo=
u, and that <em>does=C2=A0</em>require ready money. In the worst case, you =
run out of money and lose your business even as it is becoming more valuabl=
e.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a variation on this problem. Co=
mmodities futures are standardized contracts for the future delivery of som=
e commodity. The word =E2=80=9Ccommodity=E2=80=9D suggests that the commodi=
ty itself is standardized, and that=C2=A0every instance of it =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0every bushel of wheat or barrel of oil or ton of nickel or pork belly =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0is the same. But of course this isn=E2=80=99t true.[1] The o=
il industry produces oil of different compositions and purity.=C2=A0 Typica=
lly for each commodity there will be one or two sorts of futures that are h=
eavily traded and that people use as a benchmark, =E2=80=9Cthe=E2=80=9D pri=
ce of the commodity. And these futures will specify exactly what sort and g=
rade of the commodity=C2=A0can be delivered where to satisfy the futures. L=
ondon Metal Exchange=C2=A0nickel futures, for instance, are contracts for t=
he delivery of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/269=
78481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmlja2VsMjguY29tL21lZGlhL2Fib3V0LW5pY2tlbC8/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd233caae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Class 1 nickel</a>, meaning nickel=
 that is at least 99.8% pure; the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubG1lLmNvbS9lbi9tZXRhbHMvbm9=
uLWZlcnJvdXMvbG1lLW5pY2tlbC9jb250cmFjdC1zcGVjaWZpY2F0aW9ucw/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB7d9492f7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">contract specifies</a> what=C2=A0shapes and b=
rands of 99.8% pure nickel are permitted. Lots of nickel, in the real world=
, meets that specification. Lots of nickel doesn=E2=80=99t.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">If you produce Class 1 nickel, and you are worried about p=
rice risk, you can=C2=A0hedge by selling futures. If you do this, you will =
probably close out your hedge by (1) buying back the futures for cash befor=
e they expire and (2) delivering nickel to some steelmaker or battery maker=
 or other industrial user who is a customer of your regular business. But y=
ou=C2=A0<em>could</em>,=C2=A0perhaps with a certain amount of shipping cost=
s and administrative annoyance, instead=C2=A0deliver your nickel to <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTQtMDktMDMvdGhlLWdvbGRt=
YW4tc2FjaHMtYWx1bWludW0tY29uc3BpcmFjeS1sYXdzdWl0LWlzLW92ZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDM=
xMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B23e2f910" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> an LME warehouse</a> to physically settle=C2=A0the futu=
res.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you produce=C2=A0<em>other=C2=
=A0</em>sorts of nickel, and you are worried about price risk, you can also=
 hedge by selling futures. The futures you can sell =E2=80=94=C2=A0the liqu=
id standardized ones with lots of buyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0are pretty much LME=
 futures on Class 1 nickel. That is not the kind of nickel you make, and yo=
u cannot deliver your nickel to satisfy the futures contract. But it is sti=
ll basically a good=C2=A0<em>hedge</em>. If demand for=C2=A0nickel goes up,=
 (1) the price of your nickel will go up and (2) the price of LME futures w=
ill go up; if demand for=C2=A0nickel goes down, the prices of your nickel a=
nd LME nickel will both go down. The futures are correlated enough with you=
r product that this is a sensible trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On=
 the other hand you have basis risk, the risk that the=C2=A0correlation wil=
l break down and LME nickel will be worth a lot more than your nickel. And =
you can=E2=80=99t arbitrage this away, because your nickel and LME nickel a=
re not fungible.=C2=A0You=E2=80=99re short a lot of nickel futures, meaning=
 essentially that you owe a lot of nickel to the LME; meanwhile you own a l=
ot of nickel, but it=E2=80=99s not the sort that you can deliver to the LME=
.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also if everyone on the LME=C2=A0<e=
m>knows=C2=A0</em>that (1) you are a huge nickel producer, (2) you are shor=
t a lot of nickel futures, and (3) you make the wrong kind of nickel, then =
they can=C2=A0<em>bet=C2=A0</em>on the basis blowing out. If the price of L=
ME nickel goes up high enough=C2=A0then you will get margin calls, you won=
=E2=80=99t be able to deliver nickel, you=E2=80=99ll have to buy back your =
LME contracts at a loss, the LME price will go up even more, and the people=
 betting on this breaking down will make money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">This may be part of what happened to nickel this week, as Chinese nick=
el tycoon Xiang Guangda and his Tsingshan Holding Group Co.=C2=A0<a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTAvdHljb29uLWJlaGluZC1=
uaWNrZWwtcy1iaWctc2hvcnQtaGFzLXBvd2VyLXRvLWZ1ZWwtbW9yZS1kcmFtYT9jbXBpZD1CQk=
QwMzEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlc=
iZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB7136680d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">got short squeezed</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">The tycoon long believed that because he was the world=E2=
=80=99s biggest player and had ultra-low costs, he could wield unprecedente=
d influence over the nickel market, people familiar with the matter said. W=
hen prices rose above $20,000 he would consider shorting nickel, the people=
 said, because his production costs in Indonesia were as low as $10,000 a t=
on.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Xiang was aware of flaws in his s=
trategy, people familiar with the matter said. Tsingshan=E2=80=99s nickel d=
oesn=E2=80=99t match the grade used in settlement on the LME, so the contra=
cts aren=E2=80=99t a perfect hedge. However, Xiang believed the risks to be=
 manageable, the people said, even as an unidentified nickel stockpiler con=
trolled at least half of the inventories on the exchange.=C2=A0</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVuY2htYXJrbWluZXJhbHMuY29=
tL21lbWJlcnNoaXAvaGlzdG9yaWMtbmlja2VsLXJhbGx5LXNodXRzLWRvd24tbG1lLWFuZC1wbG=
FjZXMtdHNpbmdzaGFuLWluLXRoZS1zcG90bGlnaHQv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBacb55e9=
2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">And</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A record-=
breaking rally in nickel prices that led the London Metal Exchange to halt =
trading on Tuesday is putting increased pressure on the Chinese stainless s=
teel producer Tsingshan and its billionaire co-founder.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Tsingshan, the world=E2=80=99s largest stainless steel produce=
r, is rumoured to have built a big short position in nickel before a 250% r=
ally in the price of the metal this week, which saw prices top $100,000 a t=
onne.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That could put the company in a diffi=
cult position, as it is not approved to deliver nickel metal into the Londo=
n Metal Exchange to close out its position. It also raises questions about =
the LME=E2=80=99s trading structure, especially as more nickel production i=
s geared towards use in electric vehicle batteries.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt can=E2=80=99t deliver against the LME because of the c=
onfines of the exchange structure which is not geared for the EV revolution=
,=E2=80=9D Caspar Rawles, head of data at Benchmark, said. =E2=80=9CTsingsh=
an=E2=80=99s recent investments have been in battery nickel projects but th=
e exchange is rigid in requiring high purity Class 1 metal.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The LME requires nickel that is 99.80% =
purity and in the form of cathodes, pellets, briquettes and rounds. Tsingsh=
an=E2=80=99s nickel matte, however, has a 70% to 75% nickel purity.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One simple form of this story is =E2=
=80=9Cthe price of nickel shot up, and Tsingshan was long real-world nickel=
 but short nickel futures, which created a cash crunch that led to margin c=
alls and the closing of the LME.=E2=80=9D Another simple form is =E2=80=9Ct=
he price of LME nickel shot up, and Tsingshan was short nickel futures and =
long non-deliverable nickel, so it lost a ton of money on the basis.=E2=80=
=9D[2] The first form suggests that Tsingshan had a liquidity problem but n=
ot a fundamental economic problem: It was hedged but needed cash. The secon=
d form suggests that Tsingshan had an <em>actual </em>loss: Its hedge stopp=
ed working.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDkvY2hpbmVzZS1uaWNrZWwtZ2lhbnQtc2=
VjdXJlcy1iYW5rLWxpZmVsaW5lcy1hZnRlci1lcGljLXNxdWVlemU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMxMDIyX=
01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rl=
cm09MjIwMzEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e96d=
b2e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> the liquidity problem is fixed-ish</a>:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Chinese nickel company at the center of a histor=
ic short squeeze has secured a package of loans from local and internationa=
l banks to help it meet a wave of margin calls, according to people familia=
r with the matter.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tsingshan Holding Group =
Co., which faces billions of dollars in potential losses on short positions=
 in nickel futures, won credit promises from banks including JPMorgan Chase=
 &amp; Co. and China Construction Bank Corp. in meetings that ran into the =
pre-dawn hours of Wednesday morning, the people said, asking not to be name=
d since the matter is private. Some of the terms, such as how much extra co=
llateral Tsingshan needs to pledge, are still under discussion, the people =
said. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank loans are expected=
 to help Tsingshan address its immediate liquidity squeeze. With large nick=
el production facilities in Indonesia and China, coupled with surging price=
s and strong demand, the firm=E2=80=99s owner, Xiang Guangda, told bankers =
at the meetings that he=E2=80=99s confident his company can meet its obliga=
tions, according to the people. He=E2=80=99s also reviewing his hedging str=
ategy and is considering exiting the bets against nickel, one of the people=
 said.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah no when your=
 hedges blow up, the exchange shuts down, and you have to go to banks to be=
g for loans, you probably have to tell them that you are reviewing your hed=
ging strategy. It has not quite worked, has it?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Also! On Tuesday=C2=A0I made a joke about melting down nickels (the co=
ins, I mean) and like six people told me that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/26978481.266608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlZ2l=
zdGVyLmdvdi9kb2N1bWVudHMvMjAwNy8wNC8xNi9FNy03MDg4L3Byb2hpYml0aW9uLW9uLXRoZS=
1leHBvcnRhdGlvbi1tZWx0aW5nLW9yLXRyZWF0bWVudC1vZi01LWNlbnQtYW5kLW9uZS1jZW50L=
WNvaW5z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2cb7ab09" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">it is=C2=A0illegal in th=
e U.S. to melt nickels</a>. So don=E2=80=99t do that then. As I am constant=
ly saying, nothing here is ever legal advice. Imagine melting down a nickel=
 for $0.037 of metals-arbitrage profit and then realizing (1) you have to p=
ay for, like, a smelter or whatever and (2) you have to hire a criminal def=
ense lawyer. Imagine being prosecuted for it. The little blob of metal, Exh=
ibit A for the prosecution.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=
